<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-05-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-05-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="163" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d163">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 711.622/12</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Attorney General</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GTW1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gregory</hi></persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d163fn1">The same, on the same date, to the Secretary of
                                Labor.</note>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-05-09">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 9, 1917</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Attorney General</hi>: With reference
                            to the question of the interpretation of article 23 of the treaty of
                            1799 between the United States and Prussia and whether or not the treaty
                            is binding so far as this Government is concerned, I enclose for your
                            information copy of a letter dated May 8 from the President<note n="2" xml:id="d163fn2">
                                <hi rend="italic">Supra.</hi>
                            </note> giving his views in reply to my letter to him of the 21st
                                ultimo.<note n="3" xml:id="d163fn3">For a further statement
                                concerning the validity of the treaty of 1799 see instructions to
                                the chairman of the American Commission to the Prisoners of War
                                Conference, Aug. 22, 1918, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_86">p. 86</ref>.</note> A copy of the treaty article
                            referred to is also enclosed.<note n="4" xml:id="d163fn4">Enclosure not
                                printed.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>